The metaSEM package: A Brief Introduction

Mike Cheung

Mar 2023

Introduction

  • The metaSEM package (Cheung, 2015)1 conducts meta-analyses using a structural equation modeling (SEM) framework. It uses the OpenMx, lavaan, and semPlot packages at the backend.
  • The R code and the relevant files of this presentation are available at https://github.com/mikewlcheung/ESMARConf2023.

MASEM

  • Meta-analytic structural equation modeling (MASEM) is a statistical approach combining the advantages of both meta-analysis and SEM for fitting structural equation models on a pool of correlation matrices (Cheung, 20142, 20153, 20194; Cheung & Chan, 20055, 20096; Cheung & Cheung, 20167; Cheung & Hafdahl, 20168).
  • We illustrate the procedures with a meta-analysis of the theory of planned behavior (Scalco et al., 20179).
  • The variables are ATT (attitude), SN (subjective norm), PBC (perceived behavior control), BI (behavioral intention), and BEH (behavior).

Data checking

  • The primary data are a list of correlation matrices and their sample sizes.
library(metaSEM)

Two-Stage Structural Equation Modeling (TSSEM)

Stage 1 analysis: Random-effects model

  • The first stage of analysis is to combine the correlation matrices:
    • Intercept1 to Intercept10 are the average correlation coefficients.
    • Tau2_1_1 to Tau2_10_10 are the variances of the random effects.
## method="FEM": fixed-effects model
## method="REM": random-effects model
## RE.type="Diag": random-effects are independent
random1 <- tssem1(Scalco17$data, Scalco17$n, method="REM", RE.type="Diag")
summary(random1)

Stage 2 analysis: Structural equation model

  • Structural equation models can be specified in lavaan syntax. As the metaSEM package uses the RAM specification, we may convert the lavaan model to RAM via the lavaan2RAM function.
model1 <- "## Path model
          BI ~ ATT + SN + PBC
          BEH ~ BI + PBC
          
          ## Fix the variances of the predictors at 1 as variables are standardized.
          ATT ~~ 1*ATT
          SN ~~ 1*SN
          PBC ~~ 1*PBC
                    
          ## Allow the predictors correlated
          ATT ~~ SN
          ATT ~~ PBC
          SN ~~ PBC
"

## Plot the model using the semPlot package
plot(model1, col="yellow")  

## Convert the lavaan syntax into the RAM specification
RAM1 <- lavaan2RAM(model1, obs.variables=obs.variables, A.notation="on", S.notation="with")

## A[i, j] represents an ith dependent and jth independent variables.
## For example, A14, 1] represents the path from ATT to BI, which has a label of "BIonATT."
RAM1

  • We may fit a model with equal coefficients by using the same label.
## A model with equal path coefficients from the predictors to the mediator
model2 <- "## Same label on the path coefficients
          BI ~ BIonX*ATT + BIonX*SN + BIonX*PBC
          BEH ~ BI + PBC
          
          ## Fix the variances of the predictors at 1
          ATT ~~ 1*ATT
          SN ~~ 1*SN
          PBC ~~ 1*PBC
                    
          ## Allow the predictors correlated
          ATT ~~ SN
          ATT ~~ PBC
          SN ~~ PBC
"

## Plot the model using the semPlot package

  • Functions of parameters, e.g., \(R^2\), direct, and indirect effects, can be computed. A likelihood-based confidence interval (LBCI) can be computed on these functions (Neale & Miller, 199710).
model3 <- "BI ~ att2bi*ATT + sn2bi*SN + pbc2bi*PBC
          BEH ~ bi2beh*BI + pbc2beh*PBC
          
          ## Fix the variances of the predictors at 1
          ATT ~~ 1*ATT
          SN ~~ 1*SN
          PBC ~~ 1*PBC
          
          ## Allow the predictors correlated
          ATT ~~ SN
          ATT ~~ PBC
          SN ~~ PBC
          
          ## Label the error variances to calculate the R^2.
          BI ~~ ErrVarBI*BI
          BEH ~~ ErrVarBEH*BEH
          
          ## Define the R^2
          R2_BI   := 1 - ErrVarBI
          R2_BEH  := 1 - ErrVarBEH
          
          ## Define the indirect effects
          Ind_att := att2bi*bi2beh
          Ind_sn  := sn2bi*bi2beh
          Ind_pbc := pbc2beh*bi2beh
          
          ## Define the sum of the indirect effects
          Sum_ind := Ind_att + Ind_sn + Ind_pbc
          
          ## Define the direct effect
          Dir_eff := pbc2beh
          
          ## Define the total effect
          Tot_eff := Sum_ind + Dir_eff
"

## Plot the model using the semPlot package
plot(model3, col="yellow")  

## Convert the lavaan syntax into the RAM specification
RAM3 <- lavaan2RAM(model3, obs.variables=obs.variables, A.notation="on", S.notation="with")

Calculating multivariate effect sizes

  • It is not straightforward to calculate effect sizes for complicated models.
  • The metaSEM package includes some functions to facilitate this process using an SEM approach (Cheung, 2018)12. See link 1 and link 2 for two examples.

Multiple-treatment studies (MTS)

  • MTS is used when there are more than treatment groups, for example, one control group with two treatment groups. Effect sizes calculated are not independent because the same control group is used. Gleser and Olkin (2009)13 derived formulas to calculate the standardized mean differences and their sampling covariance matrix for multiple treatment studies under the assumption of homogeneity of the variances.
  • The following figure shows an SEM approach to estimate MTS. The effect sizes are:
    • \(SMD_1 = \frac{\mu_{T1} - \mu_{C} }{\sigma}\)
    • \(SMD_2 = \frac{\mu_{T2} - \mu_{C} }{\sigma}\)
  • We may make the homogeneity assumption by using \(\sigma=\sigma_{C}=\sigma_{T1}=\sigma_{T2}\). However, we may also use the control group as the standardizer, that is, \(\sigma=\sigma_{C}\), if there are reasons to believe the variances are not homogeneous.
  • The SEM approach will calculate the effect sizes and their sampling covariance matrix with the Delta method.

## Optional: only for ease of reference
gp.names <- c("Control", "Treatment 1", "Treatment 2")
  
## Sample means for groups 1 to 3
m <- c(5, 7, 9)
names(m) <- gp.names
m
##     Control Treatment 1 Treatment 2 
##           5           7           9
## Sample variances
v <- c(10, 11, 12)
names(v) <- gp.names
v
##     Control Treatment 1 Treatment 2 
##          10          11          12
## Sample sizes
n <- c(50, 52, 53)
names(n) <- gp.names
n
##     Control Treatment 1 Treatment 2 
##          50          52          53
## Assuming homogeneity of variances
smdMTS(m, v, n, homogeneity="var")
## $y
##      y2_1      y3_1 
## 0.5979628 1.1960156 
## 
## $V
##            y2_1       y3_1
## y2_1 0.03979647 0.02200887
## y3_1 0.02200887 0.04290577
## Not assuming homogeneity of variances
## The SD of the first group is used as the standardizer    
smdMTS(m, v, n, homogeneity = "none")
## $y
##      y2_1      y3_1 
## 0.6277002 1.2554949 
## 
## $V
##            y2_1       y3_1
## y2_1 0.04447739 0.02758260
## y3_1 0.02758260 0.05777168

Multiple-endpoint studies (MES)

  • MES is used when there is more than one outcome variable, e.g., mathematics and language performance. Gleser and Olkin (2009) derived formulas to calculate the standardized mean differences and their sampling covariance matrix for multiple end-point studies under the assumption of homogeneity of the covariance matrix.
  • An SEM approach can be used to calculate effect sizes on MES with or without the assumption of homogeneity of covariance matrix.
  • The following figure shows an SEM approach to estimate MTS. The effect sizes are:
    • \(SMD_1 = \frac{\mu1_{T1} - \mu1_{C} }{\sigma_1}\)
    • \(SMD_2 = \frac{\mu2_{T2} - \mu2_{C} }{\sigma_2}\)
  • \(\sigma_1\) and \(\sigma_2\) can be estimated with or without the homogeneity assumption covariance matrix.

## Optional: only for ease of reference
var.names <- c("Math", "Lang")

## Sample means for the two constructs in Group 1  
m1 <- c(2.5, 4.5)
names(m1) <- var.names
m1
## Math Lang 
##  2.5  4.5
## Sample means for the two constructs in Group 2     
m2 <- c(3, 5)
names(m2) <- var.names
m2
## Math Lang 
##    3    5
## Sample covariance matrix in Group 1    
V1 <- matrix(c(3, 2, 2, 3), ncol=2)
dimnames(V1) <- list(var.names, var.names)
V1
##      Math Lang
## Math    3    2
## Lang    2    3
## Sample covariance matrix in Group 2
V2 <- matrix(c(3.5, 2.1, 2.1, 3.5), ncol=2)
dimnames(V2) <- list(var.names, var.names)
V2
##      Math Lang
## Math  3.5  2.1
## Lang  2.1  3.5
## Sample size in Group 1
n1 <- 20

## Sample size in Group 2    
n2 <- 25

## SMD with the assumption of homogeneity of covariance matrix    
smdMES(m1, m2, V1, V2, n1, n2, homogeneity="cov")

A general model to compute effect sizes

  • Let us use the previous example in MASEM as an illustration. Suppose we want to calculate the sum of the indirect effects and direct effect as two effect sizes in a multivariate meta-analysis (this may not be a good idea due to the missing data and other reasons; see Cheung, 202214).
## Take one correlation matrix as an example
(R1 <- Scalco17$data[23])
## $`Zagata, 2012`
##       ATT    SN   PBC    BI   BEH
## ATT 1.000 0.391 0.388 0.518 0.239
## SN  0.391 1.000 0.222 0.497 0.272
## PBC 0.388 0.222 1.000 0.388 0.204
## BI  0.518 0.497 0.388 1.000 0.338
## BEH 0.239 0.272 0.204 0.338 1.000
(n1 <- Scalco17$n[23])
## [1] 1054
model4 <- "BI ~ att2bi*ATT + sn2bi*SN + pbc2bi*PBC
          BEH ~ bi2beh*BI + pbc2beh*PBC
          
          ## Fix the variances of the predictors at 1
          ATT ~~ 1*ATT
          SN ~~ 1*SN
          PBC ~~ 1*PBC
          
          ## Allow the predictors correlated
          ATT ~~ SN
          ATT ~~ PBC
          SN ~~ PBC

          ## Define the sum of the indirect effects
          Sum_ind := att2bi*bi2beh + sn2bi*bi2beh + pbc2beh*bi2beh
          
          ## Define the direct effect
          Dir_eff := pbc2beh
"

## Plot the model using the semPlot package
plot(model4, col="cyan")  

calEffSizes(model4, Cov=R1, n=n1)
## $ES
##    Sum_ind    Dir_eff 
## 0.22273508 0.08576783 
## 
## $VCOV
##              Sum_ind      Dir_eff
## Sum_ind 5.340225e-04 2.074234e-05
## Dir_eff 2.074234e-05 9.823312e-04

Other useful functions

  • There are several useful functions in the metaSEM package:
    • meta: Fit univariate and multivariate meta-analyses.
    • meta3: Fit a three-level meta-analysis.
    • metaFIML: Fit univariate and multivariate meta-analyses with missing covariates with the full information maximum likelihood (FIML) estimation.
    • indirectEffect: Calculate standardized and unstandardized indirect effect in mediation analysis.
